In TypeScript, you can use duck typing by declaring an interface for a type and then checking if an object has all the properties and methods defined in that interface. If it does, you can treat it as an instance of that type, regardless of its actual type. This can be useful for working with libraries or frameworks that don't provide type information or for dealing with dynamic data.

